# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annette-schavan
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] A federal election was held in Germany on 27 September 2009 to elect the members of the 17th Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The Christian Democratic Union (CDU), its Bavarian sister party, the Christian Social Union (CSU), and the Free Democratic Party (FDP) won the election, and the three parties formed a new centre-right government with Angela Merkel as chancellor.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] While CDU/CSU's share of votes decreased slightly, it was more than compensated by the gains of their "desired coalition partner", the liberal FDP, that won the strongest result in its history.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] CDU and CSU's former partner in the "Grand coalition", the Social Democratic Party (SPD) led by Frank-Walter Steinmeier, conceded defeat after dropping by more than 11 percentage points, receiving its hitherto worst result since the end of the Second World War (only undercut in 2017 and 2025).
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] At 70.8 percent, the voter turnout was the lowest in a German federal election since 1949.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] According to Article 38 of the Basic Law for the Federal Republic of Germany, members of the Bundestag shall be elected in general, direct, free, equal, and secret elections; everyone over the age of eighteen is entitled to vote.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] In 2008, some modifications to the electoral system were required under an order of the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The court had found a provision in the Federal Election Law by which it was possible for a party to experience a negative vote weight, namely losing seats due to more votes, violated the constitutional guarantee of the electoral system being equal and direct.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The court allowed three years for these changes, so the 2009 German federal election was not affected.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The changes were due by 30 June 2011 but appropriate legislation was not completed by that deadline.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] A new electoral law was enacted in late 2011 but was declared unconstitutional once again by the Federal Constitutional Court upon lawsuits from the opposition parties and a group of some 4,000 private citizens.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag approved and enacted the new electoral reform in February 2013.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The Bundestag is elected using mixed-member proportional representation, meaning that each voter has two votes, a first vote for the election of a constituency candidate by first-past-the-post and a second vote for the election of a state list.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method is used to convert the votes into seats, in a two-stage process with each stage involving two calculations.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] First, the number of seats to be allocated to each state is calculated, based on the proportion of the German population living there.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Then the seats in each state are allocated to the party lists in that state, based on the proportion of second votes each party received.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] In the distribution of seats among state lists, only parties that have obtained at least five percent of the valid second votes cast in the electoral area or have won a seat in at least three constituencies are taken into consideration.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The minimum number of seats for each party at federal level is then determined.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] This is done by calculating, for each party state list, the number of constituency seats it won on the basis of the first votes, as well as the number of seats to which it is entitled on the basis of the second votes.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The higher of these two figures is the party's minimum number of seats in that state.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Adding together the minimum number of seats to which the party is entitled in all of the states produces a total representing its guaranteed minimum number of seats in the country as a whole.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] In order to ensure that each party receives its guaranteed minimum number of seats when the seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë/Schepers method, it may become necessary to increase the number of seats in the Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Then it must be ensured that the seats are distributed to the parties in line with their national share of the second votes.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Additional overhang seats, or balance seats, are created to ensure that the distribution of the seats reflects the parties' share of the second votes and that no party receives fewer than its guaranteed minimum number of seats.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Balance seats are also necessary to ensure that each party requires roughly the same number of second votes per seat.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Once the number of seats which each party is entitled to receive across the country has been determined, the seats are allocated to the parties' individual state lists.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Each state list must receive at least as many seats as the number of constituencies which the party won in the state in question.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Since the 2005 election, Chancellor Angela Merkel (CDU) had governed in a grand coalition with the SPD.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] However, it was her stated goal to win a majority for CDU/CSU and FDP (the CDU/CSU's traditional coalition partner) in 2009.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Foreign minister and Vice-Chancellor Frank-Walter Steinmeier (SPD) was formally nominated as his party's chancellor-candidate at a convention on 18 October 2008.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] He aimed to form a government in which the SPD was the strongest party, but which also excluded the left-socialist party The Left.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The election campaign was considered exceptionally boring, which may be attributable to a perceived lack of charisma on the part of the leaders of the CDU and SPD.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Another reason pointed to for the sedate campaign is that the CDU and SPD both defended the record of their grand coalition, and facing the possibility of having to continue the grand coalition in a friendly manner.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Merkel was content with the low-key campaign style, which was largely seen as benefiting her party because of her high approval ratings.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] CDU candidate Vera Lengsfeld released a campaign poster featuring herself and Merkel in a way that emphasised their cleavage.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The poster bore the slogan "We have more to offer" (German: "*Wir haben mehr zu bieten*").
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] On 23 September 2009, four days before the federal elections, German police raided the Berlin headquarters of the National Democratic Party of Germany NPD to investigate claims that letters sent from the NPD to politicians from immigrant backgrounds incited racial hatred.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The federal election was the final and most important election in what is called a *Superwahljahr* (super election year) in Germany.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU and FDP, with an average vote share of around 50% in pre-election polling during the weeks before the election, were clearly ahead of the other traditional coalition partners in Germany, SPD and the Greens.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The CDU/CSU received a slightly lower proportion than in the previous election, with the Bavarian CSU receiving its lowest vote share in decades.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Overall, the CDU/CSU had their worst vote share in 60 years.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] In contrast, their preferred coalition partner, the liberal FDP, gained nearly 5% points to give it 14.6% of the vote, the best result of its history.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The big loser of the election was the SPD, which received its worst result ever in a federal election, receiving only 23% of the total party vote and suffering the biggest percentage loss of any party in German federal election history in 60 years.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] The two other parties represented in the Bundestag, the Left and the Greens, both made large gains and received the highest vote share of their respective histories.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] For the first time, The Left won constituency seats outside its traditional stronghold of East Berlin.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] As a result of the losses by the SPD and the gains by the FDP, the alliance of the CDU/CSU and FDP received an outright majority of seats, ensuring that Angela Merkel would continue as chancellor.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] Had the CDU/CSU and FDP failed to win a majority of seats, possible alternative coalitions may have included a continuation of the grand coalition of CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:annette-schavan/2009-german-federal-election] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was specifically ruled out by FDP leader Guido Westerwelle.
[src:annette-schavan/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] In the subsequent party executive meeting on 29 October 2018, both the CDU's General Secretary Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer and the Federal Minister of Health Jens Spahn announced their candidacy in the election.
[src:annette-schavan/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] This was followed by Merkel's former arch-rival Friedrich Merz, who announced his bid and his return to politics on 30 October 2018.
[src:annette-schavan/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] Spahn was eliminated after the first round, and Kramp-Karrenbauer subsequently won close-run second round of voting by 18 votes.
[src:annette-schavan/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] To be able to run as candidate for CDU leader, a person needs to be endorsed by a subdivision of the party (either the federal executive board or a state, district or local association) or the proposal by a delegate during the party convention.
[src:annette-schavan/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] The following people ran in the leadership election, having fulfilled the criteria to become a candidate in the convention.
[src:annette-schavan/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] The following CDU politicians announced their intention to run for CDU leadership, but did not receive an endorsement by either a subdivision or a delegate.
[src:annette-schavan/2018-christian-democratic-union-of-germany-leadership-election] The following politicians intended to run for the office, but withdrew their candidacy.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A federal election was held in Germany on 26 September 2021 to elect the members of the 20th Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] State elections in Berlin and Mecklenburg-Vorpommern were also held.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel, first elected in 2005, chose not to run again, marking the first time that an incumbent Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany did not seek re-election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With 25.7% of total votes, the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) recorded their best result since 2005, and emerged as the largest party for the first time since 2002.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ruling CDU/CSU, which had led a grand coalition with the SPD since 2013, recorded their worst ever result with 24.1%, a significant decline from 32.9% in 2017.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Alliance 90/The Greens achieved their best result in history at 14.7%, while the Free Democratic Party (FDP) made small gains and finished on 11.4%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Alternative for Germany (AfD) fell from third to fifth place with 10.4%, a decline of 2.3 percentage points.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left suffered their worst showing since their official formation in 2007, failing to cross the 5% electoral threshold by just over one-tenth of a percentage point.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party was nonetheless entitled to full proportional representation, as it won three direct mandates.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW) was exempt from the 5% threshold and won 1 seat, the first time it held national representation since 1949.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With a fifth grand coalition being dismissed by both the CDU/CSU and the SPD, the FDP and the Greens were considered kingmakers.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 23 November, following complex coalition talks, the SPD, FDP and Greens formalized an agreement to form a traffic light coalition, which was approved by all three parties.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Olaf Scholz and his cabinet were elected by the Bundestag on 8 December.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Irregularities in Berlin led to repeat elections in February 2023 (state) and February 2024 (federal).
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the federal repeat election meant that the FDP lost a seat in the Bundestag, while 3 other seats were moved from Berlin to different states.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2017 federal election was held after a four-year grand coalition between the CDU/CSU and the SPD.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Though the CDU/CSU remained the biggest parliamentary group, both it and the SPD suffered significant losses.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership, recognising the party's unsatisfactory performance after four years in government, announced that it would go into opposition.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] With the CDU/CSU having pledged not to work with either the AfD or The Left before the federal election, the only remaining option for a majority government was a Jamaica coalition consisting of the CDU/CSU, FDP, and the Greens.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Exploratory talks between the parties were held over the next six weeks, though the FDP withdrew from the negotiations on 20 November, citing irreconcilable differences between the parties on migration and energy policies.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Chancellor Angela Merkel consulted with President Frank-Walter Steinmeier, who implored all parties to reconsider in order to avoid fresh elections.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD and their leader Martin Schulz indicated their willingness to enter into discussions for another coalition government with the CDU/CSU.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD leadership voted to enter into exploratory discussion on 15 December 2017 and at a party congress in January 2018 a majority of the party's delegates voted to support the coalition talks.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The text of the final agreement was agreed to by the CDU/CSU and the SPD on 7 February, though was conditioned on the approval of a majority of the SPD's party membership.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 463,723 members of the SPD voted to approve or reject the deal from 20 February to 2 March, with the result announced on 4 March.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 78.39% of members cast valid votes, of which 66.02% voted in favor of another grand coalition.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel was voted in by the Bundestag for a fourth term as chancellor on 14 March, with 364 votes for, 315 against, 9 abstentions, and 4 invalid votes, just 9 more votes than the 355 needed for a majority.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The new government was officially referred to as the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's final government was subject to intense instability.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2018 German government crisis saw the longstanding alliance between the CDU and CSU threaten to split over asylum seeker policy.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Interior Minister and CSU leader Horst Seehofer threatened to undercut Merkel's authority by closing German borders for asylum seekers registered in another European Union (EU) country.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The split, eventually repaired following a summit with EU countries, threatened to bring down the government.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following his party's historically low result in the 2018 Bavarian state election, Seehofer was replaced as CSU leader by new Bavarian Minister-President Markus Söder at a party conference in January 2019, while he retained his position as Interior Minister in the Fourth Merkel cabinet.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In October 2018, Merkel announced that she would resign as leader of the CDU at the party's conference in December 2018 and step down as Chancellor of Germany at the forthcoming election, following poor results at state elections for the CSU in Bavaria and for the CDU in Hesse.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Merkel's allegedly preferred candidate for the party leadership, Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer, narrowly defeated Friedrich Merz, who had been a rival of Merkel around 2002 and had left politics in 2009 criticising her decisions and leadership.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A party convention to elect a new leader was scheduled for April but was repeatedly delayed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The election was held in January 2021, with Armin Laschet, incumbent Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, winning with 52.8% of delegate votes.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The other party in the coalition government, the SPD, also had leadership instability.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following their worst general election result since 1945, at the beginning of the new government the party elected Andrea Nahles as their leader in April 2018.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Nahles had already been elected leader of the SPD parliamentary group after the federal election in September when the party still planned to go into opposition.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She was unsuccessful in improving the party's stock with the electorate as it continued to slide in opinion polls and was for the first time in history well beaten by the centre-left party Alliance 90/The Greens at the 2019 European Parliament election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] She resigned on 2 June 2019, precipitating a leadership election for the SPD.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Progressive candidates Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken defeated the more moderate candidates Olaf Scholz and Klara Geywitz, and were elected co-leaders by the party's membership.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Their election raised prospects of the coalition government collapsing and early elections being called, although Reuters reported that the duo would seek to achieve agreement from the CDU/CSU on increasing public spending rather than allow the government to collapse.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In August 2020, the party appointed Merkel's deputy Vice-Chancellor Scholz as its candidate for chancellor at the election, despite him having lost to Walter-Borjans and Esken in the party leadership election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Cem Özdemir and Simone Peter stood down as co-leaders of the Greens after the failed Jamaica negotiations, and Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were elected as their successors in January 2018.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Dissatisfaction with the SPD and the federal government saw a rise in Greens' polling numbers throughout 2018.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They scored record results in the Bavarian and Hessian state elections in October and subsequently surpassed the SPD in public opinion, settling in second behind the CDU/CSU for the next three years.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party had its best ever showings at the 2019 European Parliament election, 2020 Hamburg state election, and 2021 Baden-Württemberg state election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They briefly polled in first place during two brief periods, first after the 2019 European Parliament election and again after the nomination of chancellor candidates in April 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left also underwent a change in leadership, with Katja Kipping and Bernd Riexinger stepping down after nine years as party co-leaders.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They were succeeded by Janine Wissler and Susanne Hennig-Wellsow at a party conference held digitally on 27 February 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler is considered a member of the party's left wing, formerly aligned with the Socialist Left faction, while Hennig-Wellsow is considered a moderate and part of the party's pragmatic wing.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both support their party's participation in federal government, particularly Hennig-Wellsow, who played a major role in the red–red–green coalition government of The Left, the SPD, and the Greens in the state of Thuringia.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Germany uses the mixed-member proportional representation system, a system of proportional representation combined with elements of first-past-the-post voting.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Bundestag has 598 nominal members, elected for a four-year term; these seats are distributed between the sixteen German states in proportion to the states' number of eligible voters.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Each voter can cast two votes: a constituency vote (first vote) and a state party list vote (second vote).
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Based solely on the first votes, 299 members are elected in single-member constituencies by first-past-the-post voting.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The second votes are used to produce a proportional number of seats for parties, first in the states, and then in the Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Seats are allocated using the Sainte-Laguë method.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] If a party wins fewer constituency seats in a state than its second votes would entitle it to, it receives additional seats from the relevant state list.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can file lists in every single state under certain conditions, such as a fixed number of supporting signatures.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties can receive second votes only in those states in which they have filed a state list.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] To qualify for proportional seat distribution, a party must receive more second votes nationwide than the electoral threshold of 5%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] This requirement is waived for parties winning at least three single-member constituencies.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As result of this waiver, parties have benefited on three occasions, such as the DP in the 1957 West German federal election and the PDS in the 1994 German federal election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Parties representing recognized national minorities are exempt from the electoral threshold.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As of 2021, these minorities are the Danish, Frisians, Sorbs, and Romani people.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Under this rule, the 2021 federal election had to take place on a Sunday between 29 August and 24 October (inclusive), as the previous 19th Bundestag had held its first sitting on 24 October 2017.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The President of Germany sets the exact date for the election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 9 December 2020, President Frank-Walter Steinmeier ordered the election to be held on 26 September 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the fourth time since 2009, the 2021 federal election was observed by OSCE, providing four experts from three OSCE states.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Center for Monitoring, Analysis and Strategy (CeMAS) found that false claims of voter fraud had become commonplace on Telegram in Germany, with accusations against Dominion Voting Systems being common despite the company's technology not being used in German elections.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] CeMAS researcher Miro Dittrich said, "We have seen far-right actors try to claim election fraud since at least 2016, but it didn't take off.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The table below lists the parliamentary groups of the 19th Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the election of Minister-President of North Rhine-Westphalia, Armin Laschet as federal CDU chairman in January 2021, he became the presumptive CDU nominee for the Union's joint chancellor candidacy.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was challenged by Minister-President of Bavaria Markus Söder of the CSU, who consistently polled well among voters and had been discussed as a potential candidate since mid-2020.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As the contest intensified in March/April 2021, Söder was backed by the CSU as well as some state and local CDU associations, while Laschet received the support of most of the CDU.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The two men failed to come to an agreement by the given deadline of 19 April, leading the federal CDU board to hold an impromptu meeting to break the deadlock.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The board voted 31 to 9 in favour of Laschet.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] After the vote, Söder announced his support for Laschet as chancellor candidate.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 10 August 2020, the SPD nominated incumbent Vice Chancellor and Finance Minister Olaf Scholz as their lead candidate for the election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz, who served as Mayor of Hamburg from 2011 to 2018, unsuccessfully sought the SPD leadership in the 2019 leadership election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Scholz was formally elected at a party conference on 8–9 May 2021, supported by 96% of delegates.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD's lead candidates were chosen via a membership vote held from 17 to 24 May 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The ticket of party co-chairman Tino Chrupalla and Bundestag co-leader Alice Weidel were elected with 71% of votes; they were opposed by the ticket of former German Air Force lieutenant-general Joachim Wundrak and MdB Joana Cotar, who won 24%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] 14,815 votes were cast, corresponding to a turnout of 48%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 21 March 2021, the FDP association in North Rhine-Westphalia elected federal chairman Christian Lindner as top candidate for the party list in that state.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] He was re-elected as chairman on 14 May, winning 93% of votes with no opponent.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The vote also served to confirm him as lead candidate for the federal election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left announced Janine Wissler and Dietmar Bartsch as their co-lead candidates on 2 May 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler was elected federal party co-leader earlier in the year alongside Susanne Hennig-Wellsow, who chose not to seek the co-lead candidacy.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Bartsch had co-chaired The Left's Bundestag group since 2015, and was previously co-lead candidate in the 2017 federal election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Wissler and Bartsch were formally selected by the party executive on 8–9 May, receiving 87% of the votes.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Due to their rise in national opinion polling since 2018, the Greens were expected to forgo the traditional dual lead-candidacy in favour of selecting a single chancellor candidate.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Party co-leaders Annalena Baerbock and Robert Habeck were considered the only plausible candidates.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Baerbock was announced as chancellor candidate on 19 April.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both Baerbock and Habeck were co-lead candidates for the party's election campaign.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A total of 47 parties and lists were approved to run in the 2021 federal election, including the seven which won seats in the 19th Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Of these, 40 ran party lists in at least one state, while 7 ran only direct candidates.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In addition, 196 independent candidates ran in the various direct constituencies.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In the table below, green shading indicates that the party ran a list in the indicated state.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The number in each box indicates how many direct candidates the party ran in the indicated state.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In July 2021, the respective state electoral committees rejected the lists of the AfD in Bremen and the Greens in Saarland.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The AfD list was rejected for formal reasons, while the Green list in Saarland was declared invalid due to a controversial nomination process, in which one third of the state delegates were excluded from the nomination convention.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Both state parties filed motions against the rulings.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal electoral committee dismissed the motion of the Saarland Greens, while the AfD list in Bremen was permitted to run in the elections.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Green Party will thus not be eligible for the proportional vote in Saarland for the first time in the party's history.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The federal election was impacted by incumbent chancellor Angela Merkel's decision not to run again, and candidates to present themselves as the natural successor to Merkel.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The 2021 European floods, with at least 184 deaths in western parts of Germany, put the climate issue back on the agenda in July.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD called for "everything to be done to stop global warming," while the CDU/CSU wanted to "speed up climate protection measures".
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] By the end of July, 56 per cent of Germans believed that the floods made it "even more important than before" to combat climate change, and 73 per cent believed the government was not doing enough in this area; only the AfD's supporters were overwhelmingly of the opposite opinion.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Following those events, six people under the age of 30 began a hunger strike in front of the Reichstag building at the end of August.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] They demanded a sincere dialogue with the leaders of the main political parties before the elections and the establishment of a citizens' convention to decide on ambitious measures for the climate.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the deadly 2021 floods, while visiting Erftstadt on 18 July, the CDU/CSU lead candidate Armin Laschet was caught laughing on camera and making jokes while President Frank-Walter Steinmeier was speaking.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Laschet was heavily criticized, despite his apology saying: "It was stupid and shouldn't have happened and I regret it." Both the CDU/CSU and Laschet's ratings suffered heavily in opinion polls and the SPD took the lead.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] During the campaign, Scholz rejected tax cuts for the rich as immoral, pledged to "increase taxes on the wealthy, spend on cleaner technology and expand social programs", and a minimum wage increase to 12 euros.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] One SPD delegate was quoted as saying: "To prepare the ground for a robust and functioning coalition, you need to make sure that no one walks out of talks looking like a loser.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In its election manifesto, The Left called for abolishing NATO in favour of a "collective security system with Russia's involvement", to which Scholz said that this is an example of minimum criteria to govern which is not negotiable.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left's lead candidates stated that those demands are a tribute to the party's historic anti-imperialist roots rather than reflecting ambitions to govern at the federal level and a discussion on the future of NATO is also being led by centrists such as France's Emmanuel Macron.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The party struck the anti-NATO demand from its immediate policy measures and Janine Wissler responded that foreign policy was more than NATO.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Gregor Gysi, a member of the left wing of the party, stated that such demands are more of a vision, are not to be implemented as soon as possible, and should not be seen as inflexible preconditions for a left-wing coalition.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens see foreign policy differences with The Left as big as financial and debt disagreements with the FDP.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Left joining the federal government would have broken a taboo due to being a democratic successor of East Germany's ruling party, and for its pacifist and anti-militarist stance, and could be seen as following examples in Spain and Sweden.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] A traffic light coalition (SPD–FDP–Greens) was seen as the more likely scenario but a R2G coalition, which would be favoured by the left-wing leadership and rank-and-file party members, was not excluded if coalition talks with FDP fail due minimum wage increase or the wealth tax.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time since 2002, the four major television broadcasters (public services ZDF and ARD with its regional networks, and commercial networks RTL and ProSieben/Sat.1) did not hold a joint television debate of only the major candidates from CDU/CSU and SPD.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Separate debates were previously prevented by incumbent chancellor Merkel, but she did not run for a fifth term in 2021, and Armin Laschet represented CDU/CSU.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Greens had only finished 6th in the 2017 election, but from mid-2018 to mid-2021 were ranked as 2nd in polls, even first in spring of 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Thus, with the traditional Two-party system of Union and SPD getting broken up and expanded to three on the federal level.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] For the first time, the traditional two-way duel debates became a three-way truel, dubbed "Triell".
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Additional four-way debates, in 2025 called *Quadrell*(quadrel), were held with leaders of the smaller parties that were part of the parliament.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Although the vote share of the South Schleswig Voters' Association (0.12%) was well below the 5% electoral threshold, due to its status of being representative of a recognised minority group (Danes and Frisians), an exception in federal law allowed the party to win one party-list seat.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Incumbents are denoted in bold and followed by *(I)*.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In Berlin, vote casting and counting was not simple as the federal election was on the same day as the Berlin Marathon, the 2021 Berlin state election and a local referendum.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The Federal Returning Officer felt compelled to request a report from the State Returning Officer Petra Michaelis.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In some polling stations ballot papers were missing or ran out and could not be delivered on the same day due to the Berlin marathon.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Ballot papers (of which there were 115 different variants in Berlin) and postal voting documents were also swapped.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Many votes were cast long after the official end of voting at 6 p.m, the last after 8 p.m. when the outcome was already being forecast.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] At least one polling station was closed due to missing documents.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In at least 16 Berlin polling stations, basic election data did not match (including impossible voter turnouts of over 100%).
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] On 29 September 2021, Michaelis announced her resignation and that of her deputy.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In 2022, the 2021 Berlin state election was declared invalid, to be replaced by the February 2023 Berlin repeat state election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] Decision making on the federal level took even longer.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] In late 2023, a repeat of the federal election was ordered in 455 of 2,256 Berlin precincts.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The result of the repeat election on 11 February 2024 replaced the original result in those precincts, resulting in the overall result of the election being recalculated.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] As a result of the repeat election, the FDP lost a seat in Berlin, resulting in the size of the Bundestag being reduced from 736 to 735 members.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p01] The SPD, Greens, and The Left each lost a seat in Berlin, while gaining one in Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, and Hesse respectively, thus keeping the total number of seats won by those parties unchanged.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] For the first time since 2002, the SPD emerged as the largest party in the Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also for the first time since 2002, the SPD swept all single-member constituency seats in the states of Brandenburg and Saarland, where they defeated cabinet ministers Peter Altmaier and Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won all constituencies in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern for the first time, including Vorpommern-Rügen – Vorpommern-Greifswald I, the seat of outgoing chancellor Angela Merkel.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] It was also the first time they won any single-member constituency seats in Saxony-Anhalt and Thuringia since 2005.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD had been written off by many political observers due to longtime internal quarrels and poor performances in prior elections, even those in early 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In the 2019 European Parliament election, they dropped to a historic low 15.8%, accelerating the decline of already deeply embattled and unpopular leader Andrea Nahles.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] When the unpopular and little-known SPD leaders Norbert Walter-Borjans and Saskia Esken nominated moderate Olaf Scholz, whom they had unexpectedly defeated in the 2019 leadership election, as Chancellor candidate in August 2020, they were widely mocked.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD sat at a distant third place in the polls and stayed there until their sudden surge late in the campaign.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] However, even at their historic poll lows around 14%, Olaf Scholz had a significantly higher personal approval rating than both his party and the other Chancellor candidates Laschet and Baerbock.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After the extreme personal unpopularity, resulting from gaffes and scandal, meant that first Baerbock and then Laschet floundered, the SPD took the lead, for the first time since early 2017, in the final stretches of the election campaign.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This surge also meant that some "paper candidates", a lot of them young, were unexpectedly elected to the Bundestag, for example Jan Plobner, Jakob Blankenburg or Fabian Funke.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That being said, the surge and eventual outcome of the election was mainly decided by older voters, who switched from the CDU/CSU to the SPD, which some attributed to Scholz being very similar in his calm and moderate leadership style to incumbent Angela Merkel.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The CDU/CSU had their worst result ever by far, eclipsing the previous worst of 31% in 1949.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] There was speculation that chancellor candidate Armin Laschet would lose election to the Bundestag; he was placed first on the North Rhine-Westphalia party list, and if the CDU gained overhang seats, that list would not be used.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Due to the CDU's bad performance in terms of single-member constituency seats, Laschet was elected to the Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The first time since 2005 that they did not win all single-member constituency seats in Bavaria, the CSU also had their worst result in history.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the catastrophic defeat were corruption scandals of several CDU/CSU politicians in spring 2021, some minor allegations even being brought against Laschet himself.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, Laschet was suffering from extreme personal unpopularity, even in his own state.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet did not have the incumbency advantage that helped moderately popular Merkel to win re-election three times, but still had to run on Merkel's legacy in voters minds.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This meant that the otherwise popular CDU/CSU platform of increasing digitization, reducing bureaucracy and moderate climate action were not taken seriously as his party had not addressed them in sixteen years of government in the minds of many voters.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In one infamous campaign moment, Laschet spoke of a "Wind of Change" in his closing statement in the first three way debate, which was widely ridiculed.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The contentious decision by the CDU establishment to have him run as CDU/CSU candidate instead of the much more popular CSU leader Markus Söder also played into this.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] During the belligerent internal selection process in spring, polls showed Söder faring a lot better than Laschet in the election, often higher than the 2017 result, and Söder was the preferred candidate of the base and the public at large.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Even fairly late into the election campaign, 70% of CDU/CSU supporters wanted to replace Laschet with Söder.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Söder publicly supported and defended Laschet, even on election night, but was accused of backstabbing Laschet's candidacy in order to become chancellor candidate in 2025.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Laschet took responsibility for the result, but initially refused to resign in hopes of becoming Chancellor through a Jamaica coalition.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The ensuing talks were plagued by leaks damaging Laschet and after Söder prematurely declared the talks to be over, both Greens and FDP decided to enter coalition talks with the SPD instead.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] After intense pressure from his party and the public, Laschet announced on 8 October 2021 that he would step down but would moderate the next CDU leadership election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] That leadership contest was the first to be decided by party members, who overwhelmingly chose conservative outsider Friedrich Merz in December 2021, after he failed in the previous two leadership elections, to Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer in 2018 and Laschet in January 2021.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was seen as a rebuff to the party establishment, who had backed Kramp-Karrenbauer and Laschet, both seen as being more moderate, aligned in both policy positions and leadership style to Angela Merkel.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens got their best result in history, nearly doubling from 2017.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Their slump in the polls was largely attributed to a number of gaffes from and the personal unpopularity of Annalena Baerbock, though polls show that a lot of Green voters migrated to the SPD in the final weeks of the campaign to ensure the CDU would not form government.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Though she won in the party-list, Baerbock lost in Potsdam – Potsdam-Mittelmark II – Teltow-Fläming II to SPD's Olaf Scholz by a large margin.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, though the Greens won 16 single-member constituency seats, all of them except Flensburg – Schleswig, the constituency of future Vice Chancellor Robert Habeck, were entirely urban constituencies.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens were also disqualified from running on the Saarland state list due to irregularities in the selection of list candidates.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens had, however, won only one seat in the Saarland in the previous two federal elections.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP had their second best showing since German reunification, gaining a few seats to maintain its fourth-place position.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] This was enough to make it a kingmaker alongside the Greens in coalition talks.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Like the Greens, they did well with young voters; among first-time voters, they received the highest vote share of 23%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In addition, while they only marginally improved their result in the West German states, their more significant increase in support in former East Germany amounted to their best performance there in the party's history.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The AfD lost seats and went from the third largest party and Leader of the Opposition to the fifth largest party in the Bundestag; however, they performed strongly in former East Germany, where they won 16 single-member constituency seats in Saxony, Saxony-Anhalt, and Thuringia.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the AfD lost vote share in Saxony, the stronger losses of the CDU still allowed them to place ahead of the CDU, becoming the most voted party in Saxony.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They also won the most party list votes in Thuringia, though only by 0.6%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for their drop in support include far less media attention, largely due to the open Chancellor's race, and large swaths of anti-lockdown and anti-vaccination voters, which the AfD campaigned hard on, voting for new parties like dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leader of the AfD faction in the Bundestag Dr.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Alice Weidel was widely ridiculed for claiming on election night that they surpassed their 2017 result if one added the results for dieBasis and Free Voters.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Left had their worst showing since 2002, when it was the Party of Democratic Socialism, slumping from 69 seats in 2017 to just 39, or 4.9%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Under a longstanding electoral law intended to benefit parties with regional appeal (as is the case with the Left in the old East Germany), any party that wins at least three constituency seats is entitled to its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Apart from this symbolic defeat, their preferred government, a left-wing red–red–green coalition, did not have a majority in the new Bundestag, and the German financial market rallied as a result.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Vice President of the Bundestag Petra Pau lost her single-member constituency of Berlin-Marzahn-Hellersdorf by a large margin.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The seat had been held by The Left and its predecessor parties since the 1990 federal election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Reasons given for the massive slump were public quarrels in the party.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] These public feuds intensified after the election, for example, the convicted former head of government of East Germany Hans Modrow, who chairs The Left's "council of elders", denounced the party.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] From February 2022 onwards, the Russian invasion of Ukraine put a strain on The Left.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Also, due to the irregularities during the 2021 elections in Berlin, affecting state level and federal level results, both elections were under ongoing scrutiny.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] According to court decision in 2022, the state election was repeated as a whole by the February 2023 Berlin state election, with losses for The Left.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A possible upcoming 2024 repeat of the federal election in parts of Berlin was a threat to the faction status of The Left in the Bundestag, and to 38 of 39 members, with only the direct seat gained in Saxony being not affected.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] With the Bündnis Sahra Wagenknecht establishing itself in October 2023 with 10 parliament members, the faction of The Left was dissolved in late 2023, losing funding and privileges by getting demoted to a group, or two in that case.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election was a watershed moment for candidates with a migration background.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] In terms of representation of ethnic minorities, one source suggested that the Bundestag would have 24 new MPs with "Balkan" ancestry.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Its list included, however, largely people of Turkish ancestry who mostly have roots in Anatolia.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The South Schleswig Voters' Association (SSW), a regionalist party only contesting Schleswig-Holstein representing the Danish and Frisian minorities in Southern Schleswig, won their first seat, becoming the first regionalist party to win seats since 1953.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Recognized minority parties are exempt from the threshold of 5%, which is how the SSW won a seat with 0.1% of the vote nationwide.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SSW last contested in 1961 and last won a seat in 1949.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] They named a felt discrimination of Northern Germany as reason for them contesting the election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Stefan Seidler was seated as their Member of the German Bundestag.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Seidler was offered to sit in the SPD parliamentary group as a guest by their leader Rolf Mützenich, but declined.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Minor parties did exceptionally well in the 2021 election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The left-wing satire party Die PARTEI had their best result ever, as did the Animal Protection Party and the regionalist Free Voters, which doubled their result and received 7.5% in Bavaria, where they take part in the state government.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A few new minor parties emerged in the 2021 election, the most notable being the Anti-lockdown and Anti-vaccination dieBasis party, which received between 1 and 1.9%.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Team Todenhöfer, founded in 2020 by notorious former CDU Member of the German Bundestag Jürgen Todenhöfer, also first contested the 2021 election, running on anti-militarism and receiving support from pro-Palestinian groups, but only garnered 0.5% of the vote.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 2021 election also accelerated the decline of the far-right National Democratic Party, which only got 0.1% of the vote.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The NPD was at a time the most successful minor/fringe party, getting 1.6% in 2005 and entering various state parliaments in former East Germany.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] A three-party governing coalition, with the FDP and the Greens joining either the SPD or CDU/CSU, was discussed as a likely outcome.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] While the grand coalition of the CDU/CSU and SPD could have been renewed, numerous representatives of both the CDU/CSU and the SPD ruled out this option before the federal election, during the campaign, and after.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On election night, SPD leader Scholz reiterated his goal to form a government, citing the fact that his party emerged as the largest in parliament.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] He expressed his intention to become chancellor and his preference for a traffic light coalition with the FDP and the Greens.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Leading figures in the CDU/CSU such as Michael Kretschmer stated that since the CDU/CSU was knocked down to second place, it should not form the government.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The FDP and the Greens, having won 210 seats between them, announced that they would talk separately before deciding on whom to support as a senior coalition partner.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The Greens and the FDP held discussions for two days after the election.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 7 October, the two parties met with the SPD for the first round of exploratory talks, with a second round on 11 October.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 15 October, the SPD agreed to more ambitious climate targets, as pledged by the Greens.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 17 October, the Greens voted to enter formal coalition talks with the SPD and FDP.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The next day, the FDP voted to do the same.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The 20th Bundestag was officially sworn in on 26 October.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 16 November, the general secretaries of the three traffic light coalition parties (SPD, FDP, Greens) announced that an agreement document was almost complete, with Scholz to become Chancellor, and that the details would be issued some time in the next week.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] On 23 November, an agreement for a traffic light coalition was finalised.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The three parties announced a number of policies, including plans to phase out coal energy by 2030, eight years ahead of the previous target, as well as lower the federal voting age to 16 years, raise the minimum wage to €12 per hour, and lower barriers to acquiring German citizenship.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Annalena Baerbock will become foreign minister, while Robert Habeck will head a new "super ministry" with responsibility for climate, energy, and economy.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Christian Lindner will become finance minister.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The SPD convention voted 98.8% in favour of approving the agreement on 4 December, followed by the FDP with 92.4% on 5 December.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] The results of the Greens membership ballot were announced on 6 December, with 86% voting to approve the coalition.
[src:annette-schavan/2021-german-federal-election-p02] Scholz was elected as Chancellor by the Bundestag on 8 December, with 395 votes of 707 cast, with 303 votes against.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] One of the oldest cathedral buildings in Europe, it was constructed as the royal chapel of the Palace of Aachen of Emperor Charlemagne, who was buried there in 814.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] From 936 to 1531, the original Palatine Chapel saw the coronation of thirty-one German kings.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Later, much expanded, it was a minster and collegiate church, becoming a cathedral briefly from 1803 to 1825, and again in 1930 when the Diocese of Aachen was revived.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 1978, Aachen Cathedral was one of the first 12 sites to be listed on the UNESCO list of World Heritage Sites, because of its exceptional artistry, architecture, and central importance in the history of the Holy Roman Empire.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The cathedral mostly uses two distinct architectural styles.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] First, the core of the cathedral is the Carolingian-Romanesque Palatine Chapel, which was modeled after the Basilica of San Vitale at Ravenna and is notably small in comparison to the later additions.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Secondly, the choir was constructed in the Gothic style.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] There are portions that show Ottonian style, such as the area around the throne, and some areas were not completed until the 19th century, in revivalist styles.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Charlemagne began the construction of the Palatine Chapel around 796, along with the rest of the palace structures.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The construction is credited to Odo of Metz.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The exact date of completion is unclear; however, a letter from Alcuin, in 798, states that it was nearing completion, and in 805, Pope Leo III consecrated the finished chapel.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] A foundry was brought to Aachen near the end of the 8th century and was utilized to cast multiple bronze pieces, from doors and the railings, to the horse and bear statues.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Charlemagne was buried in the chapel in 814.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It suffered a large amount of damage in a Viking raid in 881, and was restored in 983.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Following Charlemagne's canonization by Antipope Paschal III in 1165, the chapel became a draw for pilgrims.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Due to the enormous flow of pilgrims, in 1355 a Gothic choir hall was added, and a two-part Capella vitrea (glass chapel) was consecrated on the 600th anniversary of Charlemagne's death.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] A cupola, several other chapels, and a steeple were also constructed at later dates.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It was restored again in 1881, when the Baroque stucco was removed.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] During World War II, Aachen, including its famed cathedral, was heavily damaged by Allied bombing attacks and artillery fire, and the subsequent ground fighting when U.S. troops attacked the city, but the cathedral's basic structure survived.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Many of the cathedral's artistic objects had been removed to secure storage during the war, and some which could not be moved were protected within the church itself.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] However, the glazing of the 14th-century choir hall, the Gothic Revival altar, a large part of the cloister, and the Holiness Chapel (*Heiligtumskapelle*) were irretrievably destroyed.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Reconstruction and restoration took place intermittently over more than 30 years, and cost an estimated €40 million.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The octagon in the centre of the cathedral was erected as the chapel of the Palace of Aachen between 796 and 805 on the model of other contemporary Byzantine buildings (e.g. the Basilica of San Vitale in Ravenna and the Little Hagia Sophia in Constantinople).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The architect was Odo of Metz, and the original design was of a domed octagonal inner room enveloped by a 16 sided outer wall.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The span and height of Charlemagne's Palatine chapel was unsurpassed north of the Alps for over two hundred years.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Palatine chapel consisted of a high octagonal room with a two-story circuit below.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The inner octagon, with a diameter of 14.46 metres (47.4 ft), is made up of strong piers, on which an octagonal cloister vault lies, covering the central room.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Around this inner octagon is a sixteen sided circuit of low groin vaults, supporting a high gallery above.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This upper story was known as the *Hochmünster* (high church).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The arched openings of the lower story are only about half as high as those of the *Hochmünster*, as a result of which the lower story looks stocky and bulky.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The two floors are separated from each other by an expansive cornice.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The high altar and Imperial throne are located on the upper circuit of the Palatine chapel in an octagonal side room, covered by a barrel vault lying on an angle.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This area was connected to the palace by a passage.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Above the arches of the gallery, an octagonal drum with window openings rises, on top of which is the cupola.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] On the east end was a small apse that protruded and was, in later years, replaced by the choir.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Opposite of this, was the tiered entrance to the rest of the now defunct palace, Westwork.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Light is brought in by a three tiered system of circular arched windows.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The corners of the octagonal dome are joined with the walls with a system of paired pilasters with corinthian capitals.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The upper gallery openings are divided by a grid of columns.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] These columns are ancient and come from St.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Charlemagne allowed further spolia to be brought to Aachen from Rome and Ravenna at the end of the 8th century.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 1794, during the French occupation of the Rheinland, they were removed to Paris, but in 1815 up to half the pieces remaining in the Louvre were brought back to Aachen.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In the 1840s they were restored to their original places once more and new columns of Odenberg granite were substituted for the missing columns.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The interior walls were initially lined with a marble facade.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The round arched openings in the upper floor in the side walls of the octagon, between the columns, in front of a mezzanine, are decorated with a metre-high railing of Carolingian bronze rails.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] These bronze rails were cast 1200 years ago in a single piece according to Roman models.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The original cupola mosaic was probably executed around 800 and known from Medieval sources depicted Christ as the triumphant Lord of the world, surrounded by the symbols of the Four Evangelists, with the twenty-four elders from the Apocalypse of John offering their crowns to him.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 1880–81 it was recreated by the Venetian workshop of Antonio Salviati, according to the plans of the Belgian architect Jean-Baptiste de Béthune.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The dome was intricately decorated with a mosaic tile.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The exterior walls of the Carolingian octagon, made of quarry stone, are largely unjointed and lack further ornamentation.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The only exception is that the projections of the pillars of the cupola are crowned by antique capitals.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Above the Carolingian masonry, there is a Romanesque series of arches above a late Roman gable.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Octagon is crowned by unusual baroque vents.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Aachen Cathedral was plastered red in the time of Charlemagne, according to the most recent findings of the Rheinish Office for Monuments.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This plaster was made longer-lasting through the addition of crushed red brick.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The colour was probably also a reference to the imperial associations of the work.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The question of which geometric concepts and basic dimensions lie at the basis of the chapel's construction is not entirely clear even today.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Works of earlier cathedral architects mostly followed either the Drusian foot (334 mm) or the Roman foot (295.7 mm).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] However, these measurements require complex theories to explain the church's actual dimensions.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 2012, the architectural historian Ulrike Heckner proposed a theory of a new, hitherto unknown unit of measure of 322.4 mm, the so-called Carolingian foot, to which all other measurements in the Palatine chapel can be traced back.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This measurement is referred to as the *Aachener Königsfuß* (Aachen royal foot), after the similarly sized Parisian royal foot (324.8 mm).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Beyond this, there is a symbolic layer to the octagon.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Eight was a symbol of the eighth day (Sunday as the sabbath) and therefore symbolised the Resurrection of Jesus Christ and the promise of eternal life.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Likewise, ten, the number of perfection in Medieval architectural symbolism, is frequent in the Palatine Chapel: Its diameter (including the circuit surrounding the dome) measures a hundred Carolingian feet (i. e. ten by ten) – equivalent to the height of the dome.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The westwork (western facade) of the cathedral is of Carolingian origin, flanked by two stair-towers.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It is a two-story building, completed by a porch from the 18th century at the west end.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The bronze leaves attached to this porch, the *Wolfstür* (Wolf's Door), weigh 43 hundredweight altogether (cf. with this the Lousberg saga).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The main entrance to the cathedral, the door was cast in Aachen around 800 and was located between the westwork and the octagon in the so-called hexadecagon up to 1788.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Each leaf is divided into eight rectangles – a number which had religious symbolism in Christianity, as a symbol of Sunday, the day of the Resurrection of Jesus Christ and also of perfection (as did twelve, also) and can be found in the measurements of the Palatine Chapel over and over again.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] These boxes were framed by decorative strips, which are made of egg-shaped decorations.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The egg was considered a symbol of life and fertility from antiquity.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In Christian belief it was imbued with the even wider symbolism of Eternal Life.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The door-rings in the shape of lions' heads are wreathed by 24 (i.e. two times twelve or three times eight) acanthus scrolls – again to be understood at the deepest level through numerology.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Wolfstür's imitation of the shape of the ancient Roman temple door signifies Charlemagne's claim, to have established a New Rome in Aachen with the Palatine Chapel as the distinctive monumental building.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] There were multiple sculptures, made of bronze, including an equestrian piece probably meant as a parallel of a statue of Marcus Aurelius in Rome.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In the forehall, there is a bronze sculpture of a bear, which was probably made in the 10th century, i.e. in Ottonian times.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Opposite it is a bronze pine cone with 129 perforated scales, which stands 91 cm high (including its base); its date is controversial and ranges from the 3rd to the 10th century.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Its base is clearly Ottonian and includes an inscription written in dactylic hexameter, which refers to the Tigris and Euphrates rivers of Mesopotamia.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] According to one view, the pine cone would originally have served as a waterspout on a fountain and would have been placed in the atrium of the Palatine chapel in Carolingian times.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The upper level is characterised by an exceptionally fine brick western wall.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Inside, it bulges outward, while the outside bulges inwards, so that the Carolingian west wall can be seen as a convex-concave bulge.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Before the construction of the porch in the 18th century, the Carolingian west facade, when seen from the Narthex, was particularly evocative: a large niche, topped by a semicircular arch in the western upper level corresponded to the semicircle of the barrel vault of the lower level.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Today, the western wall is broken up by the large western window.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The large window frame dates from the Gothic period and replaced a smaller window from Carolingian times, which was probably structured as a mullion (a double arch with a column in the centre).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The modern window was designed by Ewald Mataré in 1956.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Mataré's design imitates, however abstractly, the structure of the Carolingian bronze gate inside the dome.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Bronze and unprocessed quartz form the window itself.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The function of the upstairs part of the west facade is not entirely clear.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The right of baptism (long reserved for the Collegiate Church of Mary) was at a baptismal font, which was behind the marble throne, until the end of the *Ancien Régime*.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Possibly the space was involved in these ceremonies.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Furthermore, in the western wall, under the great west window, there is a *Fensetella* (small window) even today, through which there is line of sight to the court below, the former atrium.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It is certain that the so-called *Carolingian Passage* entered this room on its northern wall, connecting the Aula Regia (King's Hall) in the north of the palace with the church.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The lower, barrel-vaulted room in the west probably served as Charlemagne's sepulchre after his death on 28 January 814 and his burial in the Persephone sarcophagus.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The floors of the western facade lying above this room were remodelled in the first half of the 14th century and in the 17th century; the tower was completed between 1879 and 1884.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Between 1355 and 1414, on the initiative of the Marienstift and the mayor of Aachen Gerhard Chorus (1285–1367), a Gothic choir was built to the east of the Octagon.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Before this there must have been a rectangular Carolingian choir.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Gothic choir measures 25m in length, 13m wide and 32m high.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Its external wall is broken, as much as possible, by windows – the surface area of the glass is more than 1,000m² and led to the name *Glashaus* (glass house).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This was conceived as a glass reliquary for the holy relics of Aachen and for the body of Charlemagne.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The design is arranged on the model of the Sainte-Chapelle in Paris, likewise a space for important relics and a royal palace chapel.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] For protection of the vault of the choir, iron rods were built in at the time of construction, to counter the lateral force on the narrow stone supports and to allow as much space as possible between them for window space.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Gathered around the octagon are several side chapels.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Aachen Cathedral houses a collection of medieval art objects from the late Classical, Carolingian, Ottonian and Staufian periods which are exceptional in their artistic and religious meaning.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In the western gallery on the lower floor, opposite the choir, the Throne of Charlemagne is to be found, which has been the object of new investigations in the past decades.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The original Carolingian throne came from the spolia of the Church of the Holy Sepulchre in Jerusalem.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The appearance of the throne and its location in the Palatine Chapel did not change with the passage of centuries.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Between 936 and 1531, thirty one German kings ascended to this throne after their anointment and coronation at the Marienaltar (Altar of Mary).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Mary) rests in the choir of the church and dates from 1220 to 1239.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Adorned with the figures of Christ, Mary, Charlemagne, Pope Leo III and the Twelve Apostles, the shrine contains the four great Aachen relics: St.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Mary's cloak, Christ's swaddling clothes, St.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] John the Baptist's beheading cloth and Christ's loincloth.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Following a custom begun in 1349, every seven years the relics are taken out of the shrine and put on display during the Great Aachen Pilgrimage.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This pilgrimage most recently took place during June 2023.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] From the vault of the dome, which is made up of eight curved faces, a wheel chandelier hangs on a long chain, about four metres above the ground, with a diameter of over four metres, which is known as the Barbarossa Chandelier (1165/1170).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This artwork was a donation of Emperor Frederick Barbarossa and his wife Beatrice.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The forty-eight candles of the chandelier are lit for solemnities of the Church.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Between 1002 and 1014, Henry II had a pulpit erected as an ambon in the east passage, which is among the most magnificent artistic treasures of the Ottonian Renaissance.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Its inscription on the upper and lower edges clearly identifies its donor as Henry II, referring to him as *REX PIVS HEINRICVS*.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The pulpit is made of an oak base and is decorated all over with filigree and precious stones, with many precious artefacts from antiquity, such as four repoussé copper reliefs with depictions of the Evangelists, as well as six ivory panels of the 6th century.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Ambon was thoroughly restored in 1816/1817 and again between 1926 and 1937.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] To this day, the pulpit is still in liturgical use for solemnities of the Church.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] A golden altarpiece, the Pala d'Oro which today forms the Antependium of the high altar was probably created around 1020 in Fulda.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It consists of seventeen individual gold panels with reliefs in repoussé.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In the centre, Christ is enthroned as Redeemer in a Mandorla, flanked by Mary and the Archangel Michael.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Four round medallions with images of the Evangelists' symbols show the connection to the other twelve relief panels with depictions from the life of Jesus Christ.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] They begin with the entry into Jerusalem and end with the encounter of the women with the risen Christ in front of the open grave on Easter morning.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The depictions are read from left to right, like a book.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Stylistically, the Pala d'Oro is not uniform.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The first five reliefs probably come from a goldsmith taught in the Rheinland and is distinguished by a strikingly joyful narration.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It probably derives from a donation of Emperor Otto III.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The other panels, together with the central group of Christ, Mary, and Michael, draws from Byzantine and late Carolingian predecessors and was likely first added under Otto's successor, Henry II, who also donated the Ambo of Henry II.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Aachen cathedral treasury includes highly important objects including the Cross of Lothair, Bust of Charlemagne and the Persephone sarcophagus.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Cathedral Treasury in Aachen is regarded as one of the most important ecclesiastical treasuries in northern Europe.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Pilgrims are able to see some of the relics every seven years when they are displayed.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The organ system of Aachen Cathedral was installed in 1939.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It consists in part of the earlier organ, installed 1845–1847, which was built by the organ builder Wilhelm Korfmacher of Linnich.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This *Korfmacher* organ had 60 stops, distributed in three works.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The current instrument was installed in 1939 by Johannes Klais (Bonn) and expanded to 65 stops, which were distributed thereafter in five works.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] To achieve a balanced sound throughout the cathedral, the parts were distributed through the cathedral: in the northwest and southwest niches of the choir are the works of the High organ, while a swallow's nest organ was hung on the east pillar of the octagon.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 1991–1993, the organ was restored by the Klais organ company and increased to a total of 89 stops.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] At this time the swallow's nest organ was turned into a new, independent instrument, which now stands in the upper church, between the octagon and the choir.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] As well as a chamber organ, the cathedral also has a small organ, called the *Zoboli Organ*.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This was built by the north Italian organ builder, Cesare Zomboli, probably some time around 1850.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The pipeworks, windbox, and keyboard survive.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The historic housing no longer exists, but the current housing was built later on the model of a north Italian cabinet organ in classicist style.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The instrument is arranged in the classic Italian style, with the typical stops of the Roman style as well.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The cathedral has eight bells hung on wooden yokes in a wooden bell frame.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The bells were cast three years after the city fire of 1656 by Franz Von Trier and his son Jakob.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] This disposition, altered from that of medieval times, has been maintained to this day, except that the Marybell has had to be replaced twice.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The largest bell or bourdon is called "Maria".
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It weighs over 6 tonnes and was cast in 1958 by Petit & Brothers of Edelbrock.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In Germany, the bells are always numbered from largest to smallest, Bell 1 is always the tenor or bourdon.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The core of Aachen Cathedral, the Carolingian octagon, was originally erected as Charlemagne's palace chapel and was also his grave.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] After his death, on 28 January 814, he was buried in his church; the exact spot is unknown, because of the lack of documentation and the ambiguity of the physical evidence.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] However, it is probable that he was buried in the Persephone sarcophagus under the west tower at the entrance to the octagon.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 1000, Otto III had Charlemagne's vault opened.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Otto of Lomello, one of the courtiers who accompanied him, recorded the event, which is reported in the Chronicle of Novalesia, written about 1026.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] A large picture representing Otto and his nobles gazing on the dead Emperor was painted on the wall of the great room in Aachen Town Hall.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 1165, on the occasion of Charlemagne's canonisation, Emperor Frederick Barbarossa again opened the vault and reinterred his remains.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] In 1215, at his coronation, Frederick II had the remains reinterred for the last time, placing them in a casket of gold and silver, known as the Karlsschrein, where they remain to this day.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Emperor Otto III was buried in the cathedral as well.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] On the explicit instructions of Charlemagne, his son Louis the Pious crowned himself king in the chapel.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Between the coronation of Otto I in 936 and 1531, thirty German kings (out of ~40) were crowned in the chapel.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The coronation itself occurred at the High Altar, followed by the enthronement on the Aachen Throne of Charlemagne (which can still be seen today).
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It is also notable that in this period, all German rulers, regardless of whether they were crowned in Aachen or not, took their position on Charlemagne's throne.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The Aachen pilgrimage (*Aachener Heiligtumsfahrt*), a pilgrimage during which the four most important religious relics of the cathedral can be seen by believers, is attested from 1238.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Since 1349, these relics have been displayed once every seven years.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] The last pilgrimage was in 2023, and had the motto "*Discover Me*".
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] As early as the Middle Ages, Aachen Cathedral was admired and imitated, as in the case of Essen Minster, the Old Tower in Mettlach and in the Alsatian Abbey Church of Ottmarsheim.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Construction elements of the octagon and choir were nominated as Historic landmarks of German civil engineering in 2007.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] According to legend, the people of Aachen ran out of funding to finish the construction of the cathedral.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] It is said that they made a deal with the devil to obtain the remaining funds, in exchange for the soul of the first to enter the cathedral.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Upon completion, the locals sent a wolf into the cathedral and the devil quickly took the animal's soul.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] Upon realizing the trick, the devil stormed from the cathedral, severing his thumb in the lion head door handles.
[src:annette-schavan/aachen-cathedral] A wolf statue sits in the entrance to the cathedral, and the "devil's thumb" can be felt inside the lion's mouth.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] After graduating from high school in 1966 at the Kaiser-Karls-Gymnasium in Aachen, Großmann studied psychology at the TH Aachen, which he completed in 1972 with a diploma in psychology.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] He then worked as an educational consultant at the advice center for parents, children and young people in Alsdorf until 1986, and as its director since 1979.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] At the same time, he worked for several semesters as a lecturer in administrative psychology at the University of Applied Sciences for Public Administration in Aachen.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] Achim Großmann was divorced and had two children.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] From 1975 to 1998, Großmann was a councilor for the city of Würselen.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] After the 1998 federal election, he was appointed Parliamentary State Secretary to the Federal Minister for Transport, Construction and Housing in the Government led by Gerhard Schröder.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] After the formation of the Grand Coalition under Chancellor Angela Merkel, the ministry was renamed the Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Development.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] After the 2009 federal election and the subsequent change in government, Großmann left office in October 2009.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] In his eleven years in office, he served under five different construction and transport ministers.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-großmann] As Parliamentary State Secretary, Achim Großmann was a member of the supervisory board of Deutsche Bahn and was involved in the preparations for the IPO.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-post] Post became a member of the Bundestag in the 2013 German federal election.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-post] In parliament, he was a member of the Joint Committee.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-post] From 2015 to 2023, Post led the Bundestag group of SPD parliamentarians from North Rhine-Westphalia, the largest delegation within the party's parliamentary group.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-post] From 2017, he served as one his parliamentary group's chairpersons, under the leadership of successive chairs Andrea Nahles (2017–2018) and Rolf Mützenich (2018–2025).
[src:annette-schavan/achim-post] In addition to his committee assignments, Post was part of the German-Egyptian Parliamentary Friendship Group.
[src:annette-schavan/achim-post] In September 2024, Post announced that he would not stand in the 2025 federal elections but instead resign from active politics by the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] Starting in 1980, Alpers studied pedagogy at the Free University of Berlin, finishing her Diplom degree in 1986.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] Subsequently, she was active in child welfare.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] She is a founder of school groups and was the leader of the first Kids Samba Group in Bremen during Carnival.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] After a speech in the Bundestag on 28 June 2013, Alpers collapsed and had to be resuscitated on site.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] A stroke as a result of an aneurysm was diagnosed, and Alpers was placed into an artificial coma.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] By the end of July, she was taken out of her coma.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] In September, she was moved to a hospital in Bremen and is currently undergoing rehabilitation.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] She handed in her Bundestag mandate effective 2 March 2015 and was succeeded in office by Birgit Menz.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] Agnes Alpers was a member of the "Socialist Unity Party of West Berlin", which was closely related to the Socialist Unity Party of Germany and the German Communist Party in West Berlin.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] From October 2007, Alpers represented the Left in a Bremen "Deputation" (a kind of local parliamentary council) for Education in the Bremen Parliament.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] In September 2009, she was elected to the Bundestag (or German Parliament) as part of the Bremen state party list.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] In parliament, she is a member of the Committee on Education, Research, and Technology.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] Despite her stroke, Alpers remained the lead candidate on the Bremen state party list and was reelected to the Bundestag in the federal election in 2013.
[src:annette-schavan/agnes-alpers] Alpers supported a cross-party bill, brought to parliament by a group of over 50 representatives on 8 November 2012, which would limit circumcision for religious purposes for only those who have reached religious maturity (14 years).
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Throughout her political career, Schavan was widely known to be a friend and a confidante of Merkel's.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Schavan was born in Jüchen on 10 June 1955.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] From 1995 until 2005, Schavan served as State Minister of Cultural Affairs, Youth, and Sports for the German state of Baden-Württemberg in the governments of successive minister-president Erwin Teufel and Günther Oettinger.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] During this time, she oversaw school education in Baden-Württemberg.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] One controversy that erupted during this time was when a Muslim teacher was banned from wearing a head scarf in school, as that was interpreted as a religious symbol, while at the same time allowing Catholic nuns to wear their traditional habits.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] The argument was that the habits of nuns and monks have an official function, while a Muslim headscarf is optional.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Schavan was regarded as a possible Christian Democratic candidate for Germany's presidency in 2004, but Horst Köhler was nominated and elected instead.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] In 2005, she attempted to succeed Erwin Teufel as Minister-President of Baden-Württemberg, but she was defeated by her rival Günther Oettinger in the internal elections of the CDU.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Oettinger's referendum win – with 60.6 percent of the vote versus 39.4 percent for Schavan – was widely seen at the time as a defeat for Teufel, who had promoted Schavan as his preferred successor.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Under the leadership of party chairwoman Angela Merkel, Schavan was re-elected vice-chairwoman of the CDU in November 2006, this time alongside minister-presidents Roland Koch, Jürgen Rüttgers and Christian Wulff.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Schavan served as Federal Minister of Education and Research from 2005 to February 2013.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Following the 2009 federal elections, she was part of the CDU/CSU team in the negotiations with the FDP on a coalition agreement.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] She led her party's delegation in the working group on education and research policy; her co-chair of the FDP was Andreas Pinkwart.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] In 2010, Schavan led efforts to enlist imams educated at German universities to improve the integration of young Muslims.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Under a plan devised by the German Council of Science and Humanities, imams were to be trained at two or three German universities, in accordance with the German curriculum.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] In addition to theology, the new preachers would also study education and community organizing.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] In a competition, the universities of Tübingen, Münster and Osnabrück were selected for the program.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] On the occasion of the sixtieth anniversary of the diplomatic relations between Germany and India, Schavan participated in the first joint cabinet meeting of the two countries' governments in Delhi in May 2011.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] In 2012, Schavan chaired the Joint Science Conference (GWK), a body which deals with all questions of research funding, science and research policy strategies and the science system that jointly affect the federal government and the 16 federal states.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Following her resignation, Schavan was succeeded by Johanna Wanka.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] In 2017, Schavan was one of the candidates considered to succeed Hans-Gert Pöttering as chair of the Konrad Adenauer Foundation (KAS) until she withdrew herself from consideration; instead, the role went to Norbert Lammert.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] In April 2023, Schavan was one of the 22 personal guests at the ceremony in which Angela Merkel was decorated with the Grand Cross of the Order of Merit for special achievement by President Frank-Walter Steinmeier at Schloss Bellevue in Berlin.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Amid the plagiarism scandal that led to the resignation of Karl-Theodor zu Guttenberg as Minister of Defence of Germany on 1 March 2011, Schavan was quoted in *Der Spiegel* as saying that "intellectual theft is not a small thing".
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Investigators found paraphrasing of secondary literature without naming the source in over 60 cases in the dissertation and thereby on 5 February 2013 revoked her doctorate degree because of "systematic and premeditated" deception.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] On 9 February 2013, it was reported that chancellor Angela Merkel had accepted Annette Schavan's resignation.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Schavan continued to deny any wrongdoing and pursued a court appeal against the process by which the university had revoked her doctorate.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] On 20 March 2014 a Düsseldorf court rejected her appeal, however.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Following the death of Pope John Paul II, Schavan – then serving as deputy chairperson of the Central Committee of German Catholics, the church's lay organisation – demanded that the "we need more lively local churches, and therefore also more autonomy [from Rome] for local parishes".
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] Ahead of the Christian Democrats' leadership election in 2018, Schavan publicly endorsed Annegret Kramp-Karrenbauer to succeed Angela Merkel as the party's chair.
[src:annette-schavan/annette-schavan] For the 2021 national elections, Schaven endorsed Armin Laschet as the Christian Democrats' joint candidate to succeed Chancellor Angela Merkel.
